","T12-L4","L1-L5","T10-L2","T9-L1"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ET10-L2\u003C/strong\u003E spinal levels provide sympathetic innervation to female pelvic viscera in the form of the sacral splanchnic nerves via the inferior hypogastric plexus. The other suggested ranges (\u003Cstrong\u003ET11-L3\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003ET12-L4\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EL1-L5\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003ET9-L1\u003C/strong\u003E) are incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe inferior hypogastric plexus is formed by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESympathetic fibres from T10-L2 levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParasympathetic fibres from S2-S4 levels (via pelvic splanchnic nerves)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hypogastric nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis plexus provides autonomic innervation to the pelvic organs including the bladder, uterus, vagina, and rectum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sympathetic innervation to female pelvic viscera via the sacral splanchnic nerves originates from spinal levels T10-L2 and travels via the inferior hypogastric plexus","The inferior hypogastric plexus carries both sympathetic and parasympathetic fibres to pelvic organs"],"references":["Yoham AL, Bordoni B. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Inferior Hypogastric Plexus. [Updated 2022 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567711/","Fowler CJ, Griffiths D, de Groat WC. The neural control of micturition. Nat Rev Neurosci. 2008 Jun;9(6):453-66. doi: 10.1038/nrn2401. PMID: 18490916; PMCID: PMC2897743.","Shermadou ES, Rahman S, Leslie SW. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Bladder. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): S